    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Cuiacius, aut Ra[e]uardus: sed Bodinus Politicus,
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Jacques Cujas"/>
    					<person name="Jacobus Raevardus"/>
    					<person name="Jean Bodin"/>
    				</position>
    				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						et Vegetius cum Hopperi vera
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Vegetius"/>
    					<person name="Joachim Hopperus"/>
    				</position>
    				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						) Iurisprudentia:
    						Bartholus, et Baldus subtiles professores:
    						Maranta, et Durandus terribiles Pragmatici: cum
    						Locupletissimo Bertachino, qui est vnus instar Om[nium]
    							<!-- Marginalia finishes in gutter. -->
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Bartolus de Saxoferrato"/>
    					<person name="Baldo degli Ubaldi"/>
    					<person name="Roberto Maranta"/>
    					<person name="Gulielmus Durandus"/>
    					<person name="Giovanni Bertachini"/>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				Definitions and divisions come from positive method. Oppositions and distinctions come from
    				scholastic subtlety. The segrets of the world once came from the most profound old men, and	<!-- CG: What would be a better way to translate veteratores and novatores? -->
    				today from the most capable young men. The doctors of distinguished pragmatic studies are not
    				Cujas or Raevardus, but Bodin, the politican, and Vegetius, together with Hopper's true study of law.
    				Bartolus and Baldo are subtle professores; Maranta and Durandus are venerable pragmatic men, 
    				together with Bertachini, most richly supplied, who is one equal to all others.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
